message.content:
We first extract and calculate the necessary figures from the three statements.

1. Operating Cash Flow Ratio
 • We use the ratio = (Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities) ÷ (Total Current Liabilities).
 • From the cash flow statement: Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –1,368,775.90.
 • From the balance sheet: Total Current Liabilities = 631,880.98.
 • Calculation: –1,368,775.90 ÷ 631,880.98 ≈ –2.17.

2. Cash Flow to Debt Ratio
 • We follow the same idea here (using total liabilities which in this case equals current liabilities).
 • Calculation: –1,368,775.90 ÷ 631,880.98 ≈ –2.17.

3. Inventory Turnover Ratio
 • Inventory Turnover Ratio = Cost of Goods Sold ÷ Average Inventory.
 • Since the beginning inventory is 0, the average inventory = (0 + Ending Inventory) / 2.
 • From the income statement, Cost of Goods Sold = 1,337,000.00.
 • From the balance sheet, Ending Inventory = 343,000.00.
 • Average Inventory = 343,000 ÷ 2 = 171,500.
 • Calculation: 1,337,000.00 ÷ 171,500 ≈ 7.80.

4. Debt to Equity Ratio
 • Use the ratio = Total Liabilities ÷ Total Owner’s Equity.
 • Total Liabilities = 631,880.98.
 • Total Owner’s Equity = 14,167,783.63.
 • Calculation: 631,880.98 ÷ 14,167,783.63 ≈ 0.04.

5. Quick Ratio
 • Quick Ratio = (Current Assets – Inventory) ÷ Current Liabilities.
 • From the balance sheet: Current Assets = 9,891,156.92 and Inventory = 343,000.00.
 • Calculation: (9,891,156.92 – 343,000.00) ÷ 631,880.98 = 9,548,156.92 ÷ 631,880.98 ≈ 15.12.

6. Current Ratio
 • Current Ratio = Current Assets ÷ Current Liabilities.
 • Calculation: 9,891,156.92 ÷ 631,880.98 ≈ 15.65.

Thus, the calculated ratios are:

{
  "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "-2.17",
  "Cash Flow to Debt Ratio": "-2.17",
  "Inventory Turnover Ratio": "7.80",
  "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.04",
  "Quick Ratio": "15.12",
  "Current Ratio": "15.65"
}
